description:
Many UK and European startups are drawn to the US - it's a huge market, huge revenue opportunities and huge funding round valuations.

But few successfully conquer the US market, and many waste valuable resources adopting the wrong go-to-market (GTM) strategy.

In this video Tom Glason shares his lessons and best practices for winning customers in the US without breaking the bank.

Tom spent over 20 years in commercial roles at high-growth b2b tech companies and over a decade as a senior go-to-market leader within VC-backed SaaS start-ups, both in the UK and US.

name: SEIS for investors
description: SEIS is a fantastic UK government tax incentive to increase investment in UK startups. When you invest in an eligible startup you can deduct 50% of your investment from this year's or last year's income tax. And you'll pay not CGT on any profits if you hold your shares for at least 3 years. Amazingly, not everyone knows about SEIS, so in this video I'll explain how it works and how to take advantage of it for your next investment.

description:

Discover the essential strategies for crafting a powerful startup data room that accelerates your growth, secures investor confidence, and streamlines collaboration. Matt, with his wealth of experience in product development and venture capital, will share invaluable tips on navigating the intersection of technology and investment. Learn first hand from Sohrab, the mastermind behind effective Notion templates, as he guides you through optimising your data room for maximum efficiency and impact.

name: What the upcoming FCA investor accreditation changes mean for you
description:
In 2001 the Government introduced a self-certification for Sophisticated Investors and High Net Worth Individuals which meant they could receive financial promotions for high-risk investments, including in startups. 

The Government is set to change the criteria to qualify as a High Net Worth Individual from an annual income of 100K and net assets of 250K to an annual income of 170K and net assets of 430K. This, alongside other changes to self-certification, will make it much more challenging for investors to qualify.

In this video I explain what these changes mean to startup founders, how they will affect your ability to raise investment, and how to adapt your fundraising strategy in light of these changes.

Important: Sign the petition opposing these changes: https://www.angels-letter.com

description:
Youve had an idea, now you just need to build it

Build a prototype to test and throw away, or go straight for a final version? No-code, low-code, or hand-code? Hire developers or outsource the development? Spend 20K or 200K to get to that first release?

Welcome to your first startup challenge! Youre not alone every founder runs into these questions. The biggest mistake founders make is spending large amounts on what they think will be a product-ready app, when they may have been better off creating a simple mock-up.

Im Anthony, founder and CEO at SeedLegals. I used to head up BBC iPlayer, Ive been doing product development for decades, and every day I see founders grappling with these problems. So Im delighted to be joined by the team at mobile apps developer Tappable, together well explore these issues and more.

If youre getting started on your first product, app or website, this webinar could save you thousands in avoiding wasted product development, and get you a winning app sooner and more efficiently.

name: Should I raise 150K now or 250K later?
description:

In this video we explain all the variable, to help you come up with the optimal strategy for your business, and how SeedLegals can help you whichever way you go.

description: Is the market down? Are investors dropping out? Are valuations down? Here's what we're seeing at SeedLegals, and how to tune your plans to preserve cash and increase your investability.

name: Claiming SEIS-EIS loss relief for investors
description: Startup not working out? Unable to raise investment? Startup life is tough, you have many hard choices to make. If you're not profitable and can't raise money you have three choices: Sell the company, go into 'holding pattern', or shut down. Here we look at how each choice affects your investors' SEIS/EIS, and how to give them the best outcome for supporting you on your journey.

name: vid 2
What is a clean cap table? And why it's probably not what you were expecting.
description: Occasionally customers contact us saying they want a "clean cap table", and to do that they want to set up a Special Purpose Vehicle ("SPV") or nominee structure to reduce the number of shareholders on their cap table. Actually a clean cap table is not that you have few shareholders, it's that the founders have the majority of the shares, that you don't have toxic convertible notes or investments. Here's how to really achieve a cap table that keep you investment-ready and avoids investors blocking your ability to run your company.

name: The Art of the 5 Year Business Plan
description: Your investors will be expecting your pitch deck to include a 3 or 5 year business plan. Here's why it will almost certainly be wrong, why you need to do it anyway, and how to make it compelling for investors.
